  "market_context": "After a bullish change of character confirmed by break of structure above a major high on 1H, price retraced but did not reach the extreme order block or FVG; instead reversed upward before hitting those zones.",
  "key_observation": "Price reversed before reaching the extreme LTF order block and FVG due to inefficiency in the retracement wave and absorption of momentum from traders anticipating continuation of the new bullish trend.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a bullish change of character on EURUSD 1H after price broke and closed above the most recent major high following mitigation of HTF demand zone and taking out inducement.",
    "Step 2: On the 15-minute chart, noted two potential long entry zones: the extreme LTF order block (OB) and the fair value gap (FVG) located just below it.",
    "Step 3: Observed that price began retracing downward toward these zones but reversed upward before reaching them, resulting in a missed trade for OB/FVG limit orders placed at extremes.",
    "Step 4: Explained the reversal was caused by inefficiency formed during the retracement wave, preventing price from reaching the extreme OB/FVG and instead absorbing bullish momentum from traders expecting trend continuation.",
    "Step 5: Compared outcomes: a trade entered at the FVG would have been triggered and reached take profit, whereas an order placed at the extreme OB would not have been activated."
  ],
  "outcome": "FVG entry would have been filled and hit take profit; extreme OB entry would have been missed.",
  "lessons": "Entering from the FVG (rather than the extreme OB) reduces risk of missing trades when price reverses early due to inefficiency and momentum absorption, even if it slightly reduces reward-to-risk ratio.",
